    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Price Per Unit Weight Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Grocery shopping becomes significantly smarter when you compare products by their unit price rather than their total price. This calculator takes any product's price and weight, in grams, kilograms, ounces, or pounds, and shows you the equivalent price per kilogram, per pound, per 100 grams, and per gram. This makes it effortless to compare different package sizes, brands, and even products sold in different weight units.
      </p>
      <p>
        Enter the total price, the weight amount, and select the appropriate weight unit. The calculator handles all the conversions between metric and imperial units instantly. Use it right in the grocery store on your phone to decide between the 400g bag at $4.99 and the 750g bag at $8.49. The one with the lower price per kilogram is the better value.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Price Per Weight Formulas</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator converts all weights to grams as a common base, then computes: <strong>Price per gram = Total Price / Weight in grams</strong>. From there, Price per kg = Price per gram x 1,000; Price per lb = Price per gram x 453.592; Price per 100g = Price per gram x 100. The conversion factors between units are: 1 kg = 1,000 g, 1 oz = 28.3495 g, 1 lb = 453.592 g.
      </p>

      <h3>Smart Shopping with Unit Pricing</h3>
      <p>
        Many stores display unit prices on shelf labels, but they are not always consistent. One product might show price per ounce while its competitor shows price per pound. This calculator normalizes everything so you can compare directly. When products are on sale, the unit price is especially important because discounts on smaller packages sometimes still leave them more expensive per unit than the regular-priced larger package.
      </p>

      <h3>Bulk Buying Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        A lower price per kilogram does not always mean a smarter purchase. Consider shelf life, storage space, and how quickly you will consume the product. Buying 5 kg of flour at a great unit price is wasteful if half of it expires before you use it. For non-perishable items you regularly use, bulk buying at a lower unit price is almost always a good idea. For perishable goods, balance the unit price savings against potential food waste.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate price per kilogram?</h3>
      <p>
        Divide the product price by its weight in kilograms. If the weight is in a different unit, convert it first: 1 kg = 1000 g, 1 kg = 2.20462 lb, 1 kg = 35.274 oz. For example, a $5.99 package weighing 500g has a price per kg of $5.99 / 0.5 = $11.98/kg.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I compare products sold in different weight units?</h3>
      <p>
        Convert both to the same unit using this calculator. Enter each product's price and weight with its original unit, and the calculator shows price per kg, per lb, and per 100g for both. The one with the lower price per kg is the better deal by weight.
      </p>

      <h3>Is buying in bulk always cheaper per unit weight?</h3>
      <p>
        Usually, but not always. Larger packages generally have a lower price per unit weight, but stores sometimes price smaller sizes more aggressively during sales. Always check the unit price rather than assuming the bigger package is the better deal. Also consider whether you can use the product before it expires.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do stores show price per 100g instead of per kg?</h3>
      <p>
        Price per 100g is common in many countries, especially in Europe and Australia, because it produces more readable numbers for small or moderately priced items. A price of $1.20 per 100g is easier to compare at a glance than $0.012 per gram. Both are valid metrics; this calculator shows all of them.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert price per pound to price per kilogram?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the price per pound by 2.20462 to get the price per kilogram. Since 1 kg = 2.20462 lb, a product costing $3.00/lb costs $3.00 x 2.20462 = $6.61/kg. This calculator handles the conversion automatically when you select the weight unit.
      </p>

